<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio ACIR Roundup on Chiapas Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401143294 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1259 
GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0401143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Information Panorama" newscast] </F>
  [Text] On the third day of clashes in Chiapas, the Zapata 
National Liberation Army [EZLN] once again attacked the 31st 
Military Zone, very close to San Cristobal de las Casas. The 
Mexican Army successfully repelled this attack, and immediately 
reinforced military operations in the municipality. Meanwhile, 
the Army has recovered the municipalities of Ocosingo and Las 
Margaritas, although clashes continue in the surrounding areas. 
  According to military sources, so far there have been 86 
deaths in these clashes. Altamirano municipality remains under 
the control of the armed group that has begun to demolish the 
municipal palace. 
  Commenting on the situation in Chiapas, President Carlos 
Salinas de Gortari said there is no time or place in Mexico for 
divergence that cannot be solved according to the law. He 
admits there are certain shortages and inequalities in that 
state, but he warns that violence will delay a true solution of 
the problems. 
  The Government Secretariat assured that the groups active in 
Chiapas represent a mixture of interests by local and foreign 
persons who are linked to violent groups operating in Central 
America. Government Under Secretary Socorro Diaz admitted that 
the Mexican Government learned several months ago about the 
existence of illegal groups in that area. 
  Following orders from the Executive Branch, new procedures 
will be established to study the problems in Chiapas. The 
Social Development Secretariat will review the work being done, 
and with the social organizations of that state, it will define 
the projects for the new year. 
  Meanwhile, Chiapas Governor Elmar Setzer has urged the 
people 
of Chiapas to be prudent, and he trusts the Army will shortly 
reestablish peace in Chiapas. Elmar Setzer denied that he is 
planning to resign. 
  Meanwhile, EZLN leaders reiterated they will not negotiate 
with the government so long as the government does not turn 
power over to the people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

