<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Sources' Disclose Increased Clashes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0401173394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1627 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0401173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tuxtla Gutierrez (Mexico), 4 Jan (EFE) -- 
Military sources have disclosed that clashes between the Armed 
Forces and the Zapata National Liberation Army (EZLN) increased 
in recent hours near Ocosingo, in Chiapas, as the rebels are 
drawing closer to the capital of this state in southern Mexico. 
  According to unofficial reports, at least 200 people were 
killed in the fighting but it is estimated that there could be 
more bodies scattered in jungle areas and in the cities, but 
access to these sites have been denied to reporters. The 
Mexican Army closed the roads that link Tuxtla Gutierrez, the 
capital of Chiapas, with San Cristobal de las Casas -- where the 
insurrection began on Saturday -- because the rebels are 
approximately 16 km from Tuxtla Gutierrez, military sources told 
EFE. 
  The Armed Forces established a general headquarters outside 
Tuxtla Gutierrez and are keeping all entry into the city under 
very close surveillance. In addition, these forces are totally 
occupying Chiapa de Corzo, one of the main tourist zones, which 
the rebels could use to enter the area. 
  Sources close to the Army noted that 25 rebels were captured 
and that "Commander Marcos" (who headed the attack on San 
Cristobal de las Casas) could be among them. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

