<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Expels Rebels From Altamirano; 121 Dead </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501030594 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0157 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501030594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tuxtla Gutierrez, Mexico, 4 Jan (EFE) -- The Mexican 
Army has expelled the rebels from the town of Altamirano, which 
was their last bastion in the Mexican State of Chiapas and where 
a heavy exchange of fire is still going on, media sources said 
today, Tuesday. 
  The rebels seem to have taken refuge in the Lacandon Jungle, 
to where they have been pushed by Army troops, who chase and 
bomb them, journalist of the Tuxtla Gutierrez daily "CUARTO 
PODER" told EFE. 
  Military sources told our informants that the chase has 
extended to the town of San Juan Chamula, in the Lacandon 
Jungle, where residents captured four rebels who were armed with 
harquebus-type shotguns. 
  The Army expelled the rebels from the town of Altamirano, 
the 
last of seven towns they had occupied and which still remained 
under their control. 
  In Altamirano shooting between the rebels and Army was still 
heard, however. Fighting has left at least 121 dead, half of 
whom are Zapatista rebels, according to official sources. 
  A journalist of the daily "CUARTO PODER" told EFE that the 
Mexican Army controls totally three of the four municipalities 
in which the rebels had concentrated. 

</TEXT>

