<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bishop Spotlights Army's Alleged Executions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501034394 Paris AFP in Spanish 0235 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501034394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Gerardo Tena] </F>
  [Text] San Cristobal de las Casas, Mexico, 4 Jan (AFP) -- 
Samuel Ruiz, San Cristobal de las Casas bishop, spotlighted 
today reports on the execution of rebel Indians by the Mexican 
Army in Chiapas State, site of fighting in the past few days. 
  There are reports that certain guerrillas captured by the 
Army have been executed, the bishop said during a news 
conference. The bishop also said that it is "foreseeable" the 
civilian population will be repressed by the Army, because there 
has not been a delimitation of the battlefields where soldiers 
are fighting the guerrilla Zapatista National Liberation Army 
(EZLN). 
  The bishop, who held a news conference minutes before the 
Air 
Force bombed a hill in the outskirts of San Cristobal, said that 
approximately 12,000 Army troops are deployed in the strife-torn 
region. 
  The prelate, who is involved in the defense of human rights, 
particularly that of poor Indians, said that the Army's massive 
military response "seems to be a decision" to totally crush the 
movement, and in this framework "there are many wounded people 
who have not even been counted." 
  Ruiz called on the two sides to agree on a cease-fire so as 
to begin negotiations with the church mediation to lay the 
foundations for a concerted effort to end the conflict, which 
broke out on 1 January when EZLN members violently occupied five 
municipalities in the southern State of Chiapas. 
  He recommended that the situation be observed by national 
and 
foreign human rights observers, and he mentioned that Americas 
Watch, Amnesty International, and Lawyers of Minnesota are 
willing to come to the region to observe the situation. 

</TEXT>

