<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rejects U.S. Reports ARENA Leader </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0601012494 San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY in Spanish 5 Jan 
94 pp 3, 21 </F>

<F P=103> PA0601012494 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador EL DIARIO DE HOY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Alfredo Cristiani complained yesterday 
that U.S. newspapers only publish "unilateral reports" that 
adversely affect ARENA [Nationalist Republican Alliance], but 
they do not publish reports "on the thousands of murders 
committed" by the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front 
(FMLN) during the war. 
  The president thus rejected reports published in Washington 
on alleged U.S. pressure exerted on the late ARENA leader 
Roberto d'Aubuisson in 1984 to prevent an attack on Thomas 
Pickering, who was serving as U.S. ambassador at the time. 
Cristiani added that a report appearing in the U.S. newspaper 
THE WASHINGTON POST, which cited official documents on the 
recent Salvadoran war that had been kept secret until recently, 
are based on "unconfirmed" information. 
  President Cristiani admitted that General Vernon Walters 
visited his country in 1984. He added, however, this was 
related to the selection of an acting president, who turned out 
to be Alvaro Magana, in view of the political crisis facing the 
country at that time. 
  He added that the U.S. soldier met with Major d'Aubuisson, 
who died in 1992, because he was among the most prominent local 
politicians in his capacity as president of the Constituent 
Assembly, and he added that "they were searching for a consensus 
person to occupy the Presidency while the Constitution was being 
drafted." 
  Cristiani said he has all the documents that the United 
States declassified, adding that he could list thousands of 
murders involving the FMLN, including that of Presidency 
Minister Dr. Antonio Rodriguez Porth in June 1989. 
  The president criticized an alleged propaganda campaign 
unleashed against his party. He said that all those documents 
bear a headline stating that the Department of State does not 
guarantee the veracity of the information and that this is 
simply information collected by chance. 
  U.S. President Bill Clinton made public in November 1993 a 
large amount of secret information on the Salvadoran war 
(1980-92). Publication of this information in U.S. newspapers 
has already unleashed several polemics in El Salvador. 

</TEXT>

