<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cristiani Accuses FMLN of Having Weapons, Violating Accords </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0601044494 Paris AFP in Spanish 2115 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0601044494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Salvador, 4 Jan (AFP) -- Salvadoran President 
Alfredo Cristiani today said the former Salvadoran guerrillas 
still maintain weapons used during the past civil war, thereby 
violating the peace accords that call for the total destruction 
of war materiel belonging to the former rebels. 
  In a news conference, Cristiani declared: "I am convinced 
that nobody in his right mind could guarantee that the FMLN 
(Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front) has destroyed all of 
its weapons, because we all know this is not true." 
  Additionally, Cristiani revealed that the government has 
thousands of documents linking the FMLN to the assassination of 
rightist leaders and ideologists during the past decade, the 
responsibility of which was later denied by the former 
guerrillas. According to Cristiani, Presidency Minister Antonio 
Rodriguez Porth appeared to be one of those victims. He was 
killed nine days after the current government took office in 
June of 1989. 
  The Salvadoran president also stated that the UN Observers 
for El Salvador (Onusal) were kept informed of the existence of 
weapons and groups of former guerrillas who are still armed. 
  "They have had weapons in Nicaragua, and they have weapons 
in 
our country," insisted Cristiani, who did not give details on 
the alleged weapons still in the hands of former rebels. 
  In August of 1993, Onusal issued a communique proclaiming 
the 
total destruction of the FMLN arsenals, although it warned that 
there was a very good chance that weapons could turn up in the 
future in isolated cases. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

