<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Discusses Arms Trafficking, Possible Amnesty </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501174494 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 3 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0501174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ciro Ortega from the "RPC Television News" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara Galimany has said that 
there is illegal trafficking of weapons through Panama en route 
to Colombia. The president made this statement at the Supreme 
Court, where he discussed government plans for 1994. According 
to the president, 1994 is a year in which much attention will be 
focused on the elections. He pointed out that the next 
president will have to face the challenge of reorganizing the 
government's program so that the country can be prepared to 
manage the interoceanic waterway once it is turned over to 
Panamania in 2000. 
  [Begin recording] [Endara] These next five years will be 
crucial in Panamanian history. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Molirena [Nationalist Liberal 
Republican Movement] might leave the ruling alliance. Have you 
made the necessary changes? 
  [Endara] I will not get involved in political matters. I 
realize that what may occur in politics has repercussions inside 
my government, but I want it to have the minimum repercussion 
possible. 
  [Reporter] Will there be political amnesty this year? 
  [Endara] Political amnesty is granted by the Legislative 
Assembly, not me. 
  [Reporter] The Catholic Church is concerned about the large 
number of weapons on the streets in the hands of third parties. 
What can the government do about this prior to the elections? 
  [Endara] I am not aware of the Church's concerns in this 
regard. I believe there definitely is arms trafficking, but -- 
thank God -- according to intelligence reports, the weapons are 
only passing through Panama and do not stay here, at least not 
in large numbers. 
  [Reporter] Where are those weapons going? 
  [Endara] Usually to Colombia. [end recording] 
  President Endara also pointed out that he has no plans to 
grant amnesty to Colonel Eduardo Herrera. As for his 
administration, he pointed out that he has fulfilled his role in 
a transition government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

