<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Union Secretary Says Workers Favor Permanence of U.S. Bases </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0601004594 Panama City Telemetro Television Network in 
Spanish 1730 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0601004594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Telemetro Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Francilino Diaz; from the "Telemetro Reports" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] Ray Bishop, Local 907 Armed Forces Employees Union 
secretary, has challenged any firm or institution that operates 
in the Panama Canal reverted areas to prove that their workers 
do not favor either the permanence of the military bases in 
Panama or the candidacy of Ruben Dario Carles for president of 
the Republic. 
  [Begin Bishop recording] [Word indistinct] the sectors that 
disagree with the position held by the vast majority of the 
workers are precisely the managers who are also businessmen. I 
even challenge them.... [pauses, changes thought] We represent 
the workers of the military bases. We are answering for those 
workers, and 85 to 90 percent of them support the candidacy of 
Professor Ruben Dario Carles, not only because his political 
campaign is based on protecting jobs on the military bases but 
also because he is inclined to protect the positive economic 
revenues that enter our country due to those bases. [end 
recording] 
  Bishop said that the individuals who oppose these two issues 
want to divide the reverted areas among themselves and continue 
with the ongoing negligent attitude after the year 2000. 
  [Begin Bishop recording] This is the end of the line. Here, 
Panamanians as a whole must demand that the government that will 
take the helm of our country in 1994 effectively legislate in 
favor and to the benefit of the majority of Panamanians, not 
just a small group of businessmen and politicians. [end 
recording] 
  Bishop's recent statements in this same vein prompted 
several 
sectors to state that Local 907 cannot speak for all workers of 
the reverted areas. Bishop says, however, that those who oppose 
his views have never been interested in the needs of the 
Panamanian people. 
  [Begin Bishop recording] Together, let's try to restructure 
our country as Panamanians and, those who are elected in 1994, 
as public employees. [sentence as heard] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

