<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cardenas Laments Mexican Uprising, Rejects Any Parallel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0501175394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1531 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0501175394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] La Paz, 4 Jan (EFE) -- Bolivian Vice President 
Victor Hugo Cardenas, of Aymara descent, today lamented the fact 
that indigenous peoples in Mexico had chosen the path of armed 
struggle, emphasizing that in Bolivia there will not be a 
similar situation because the government has begun to resolve 
the problems of indigenous peoples. 
  Of Bolivia's population of 6.4 million, 70 percent are of 
Aymara, Quechua, and Guarani descent, in addition to some 20 
Amazon tribes. Most of them live in poverty or in extreme 
poverty. 
  In 1993, international organizations considered that 
Bolivian 
peasants were the planet's poorest people. 
  "I lament the fact that in Mexico they decided to take up 
arms, but in Bolivia there will be no such movements because the 
demands from those sectors are being met, despite the fact that 
for many years they had been sidelined," the vice president said. 
  Cardenas added that "the exclusion of indigenous peoples is 
being overcome in Bolivia within the framework of the democratic 
system," noting that the government has taken major steps "to 
tackle indigenous people's problems," though he admitted that 
such steps "are not enough -- but it is important to begin, in 
order to find answers within the next few years." 
  The government of President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada has 
announced that as of this year it will implement the "people's 
participation" program, which will be based on traditional 
institutions: the "ayllu" (indigenous community) and the "ayni" 
(mutual cooperative work, "today for you, tomorrow for me") in 
the areas of education and health. 
  The vice president emphasized that the work by the 
government 
"will leave them with no justification for violent action," 
adding that Bolivian democracy will also contribute to "avoiding 
the creation of radical indigenous movements." 
  Some movements of apparent indigenous origin have appeared 
in 
Bolivia over the past eight years, movements that have tried to 
vindicate -- through terrorism and attacks -- objectives such as 
social justice for indigenous people, but they were not 
supported by the people and were dismantled by the security 
organs of the state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

