<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   12,000 Soldiers Involved in Counteroffensive </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501151994 Paris AFP in Spanish 1037 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by special AFP correspondent Francis Kohn] </F>
  [Text] San Cristobal de Las Casas, Mexico, 5 Jan (AFP) -- 
AFP has confirmed that considerable reinforcements sent by the 
Mexican Army, including a column of armored personnel carriers, 
arrived in San Cristobal de las Casas (southern Mexico) on the 
night of 4 January as part of an operation launched against the 
Zapatist rebels who are beginning to retreat. 
  Fifteen armored personnel carriers, jeeps equipped with 
light 
artillery and several ambulances crossed San Cristobal on 
Tuesday around 2200 apparently heading toward Ocosingo, which 
was still occupied by the rebels of the Zapatist National 
Liberation Army [EZLN]. 
  Military authorities are still keeping quiet regarding the 
ongoing operations against the EZLN, which launched a surprise 
attack on 1 January. Apparently, some 12,000 soldiers are 
participating in the counteroffensive. 
  According to several witnesses, the rebels -- who reportedly 
total 1,000 -- continued their withdrawal from various towns on 
Tuesday, moving their casualties to the mountain area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

