<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Recovers Regions Taken by Zapatist Rebels </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501151094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1132 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501151094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] San Cristobal de las Casas, 5 Jan (NOTIMEX) -- 
The authorities announced that the Mexican Army has been able to 
recover several townships taken over last Saturday by an armed 
group in the southeastern State of Chiapas, although there are 
still some regions that are considered "unsafe." 
  Official Spokesman Eloy Cantu stated last night that the 
government had virtually recovered control of San Cristobal de 
las Casas, Ocosingo, Las Margaritas, and Altamirano, population 
centers occupied by the so-called Zapatist National Liberation 
Army [EZLN]. 
  Nevertheless, in reporting on the events that took place in 
Chiapas, the aforementioned Mexican Government spokesman 
explained that "there are still specific areas where conditions 
of insecurity still persist." "Institutional life and normalcy 
are painstakingly being recovered, in other words, with each 
passing moment civilian authority is being reinstated," Cantu 
stated. 
  Dozens of bodies with evidence of bullet wounds where laying 
along Ocosingo's streets after the Army was able establish 
control of the last population center taken by the armed group. 
The rebel groups decided to withdraw to the mountain region 
located in the north-central part of Chiapas. 
  In Ocosingo, located 800 kms south east of Mexico City, 
Zapatista members attempted to hold on to the last population 
center it originally took. After taking over the first four 
communities, the up until now unknown EZLN began to appear in 
other communities such as Abasolo, Chanal del Carmen, and 
Oxchuc. During the last few hours the rebel group also withdrew 
from Oxchuc. [Passages omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

