<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Proposes Framework for Talks With Rebels </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501144394 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1335 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Miguel Angel Velasquez] </F>
  [Text] San Cristobal de las Casas, Chiapas State, 5 Jan 
(NOTIMEX) -- Through its official spokesman, Eoloy Cantu 
Segovia, the Mexican Government this morning asked the armed 
rebels operating in this area of the state to hold talks and lay 
down and surrender their weapons. 
  Talking to reporters in this city, Cantu Segovia, who is 
also 
the Government Secretariat's senior officer [oficial mayor], 
conveyed the government's readiness to begin talks at once with 
the armed group. He added "that for the purpose of avoiding 
greater loss of lives, the Federal Government is reiterating its 
readiness to establish an immediate dialogue with the armed 
group that began its operations the first of this year." 
  To begin this dialogue, the government also proposed a 
framework of understanding that consists of four points: 
  1. The ending of hostilities and attacks on towns and 
persons. 
  2. The laying down and surrendering of weapons, including 
the 1.5 tonnes of dynamite stolen on 31 December. 
  3. The return of hostages and kidnapped persons. 
  4. The identification of interlocutors and leaders of the 
armed group. 
  The official spokesman affirmed that "with strict adherence 
to the absolute respect for human rights, the government will 
make the allowances contemplated by the law with those who 
accept this invitation to a dialogue and lay down and surrender 
their weapons." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

