<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rebels Occupy Town Near Guatemalan Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0501201094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1849 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0501201094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] San Cristobal de las Casas (Mexico), 5 Jan (EFE) -- 
Today, several Social Security workers confirmed to EFE that 
some 1,000 rebels of the Zapatist National Liberation Army 
[EZLN] are still occupying the city of Guadalupe Tepeya, located 
only 800 meters from the Guatemalan border. 
  The workers, who traveled from Guadalupe Tepeya to San 
Cristobal de las Casas today, said that the rebels have mined 
the road leading to Guadalupe Tepeya and kidnapped 100 
civilians. The informants could not state whether there are any 
members of the Public Forces among the hostages. The workers 
added that the residents of Guadalupe Tepeya had noticed some 
unusual activity since 19 December, and that in the last hours 
the power lines were sabotaged. 
  Thus far there are no reports of confrontations between the 
Army and the rebels in that area of the Mexican State of 
Chiapas. Guadalupe might be the only city that remains occupied 
by the EZLN, following its declaration of war on the Mexican 
Government on 1 January. 
  Meanwhile, some fighting is still being reported in the 
neighborhood of Ocosingo as well as bombings on the outskirts of 
San Cristobal de las Casas. A radio station commentator said 
that the Mexican Army bombed three vehicles with 16 reporters 
that were heading to the combat zone near San Cristobal de las 
Casas, but the reporters escaped unharmed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

