<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Congressional Commission To Probe Uprising </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0601043494 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 1933 
GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0601043494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Luis Armenta from the "Vector 21" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Permanent Commission of Congress has reached an 
agreement on the violent events in Chiapas State. The 
legislators proposed the creation of a commission comprising 
senators and deputies that would be tasked with investigating 
the events in the country's southeast. The legislators are also 
demanding from the authorities more information on the 
insurrection in Chiapas. 
  Here are some of the proposals that the Permanent Commission 
has made on the Chiapas case. The proposals are read by 
Institutional Revolutionary Party Deputy Efrain Zuniga Galeana. 
  [Begin Zuniga recording] The Permanent Commission of 
Congress 
proposes: 
  1. To urge those who are carrying out armed protests to 
contribute to an end of the fighting, to accept mediation, and 
to contribute -- together with the authorities and society -- to 
the establishing conditions suitable for dialogue and 
negotiations. 
  2. The people are entitled to systematically receiving 
truthful and timely information. 
  3. The formation of a group composed of legislators from the 
three working commissions. The group will be responsible for 
securing the necessary information to suggest, within the 
framework of its attributions and responsibilities, political 
solutions to the situation that prevails in Chiapas State. [end 
recording] 
  The legislators of the Permanent Commission also said that 
in 
order to safeguard the country's independence and sovereignty, 
it is necessary to maintain constitutional order in Chiapas 
State. 

</TEXT>

