<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   * Day Care in Agricultural Centers Established </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94P2O183A </F>
<F P=103> 94P2O183A </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:CSO 

  [Editorial Report] Havana GRANMA in Spanish of 14 December 
1993 on page 2 reports that, although the economic situation 
prohibits the building of new day-care centers, resolution 203 
of November 1993 provides for day-care centers for children ages 
2 through 5 to be established in sugar- and agricultural-related 
work centers. According to the article, State resources budgeted 
for food services and raw materials may not be applied to day 
care; rather, the work centers must provide for day care from 
their own resources. If a center does not have the means to 
establish day care, then food services will be suspended. Health 
services for the children include a guaranteed supply of potable 
and boiled water, according to the article. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

