<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Indigenous Group Requests Red Cross Intervention in Chiapas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0601014094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2358 GMT 5 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0601014094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, 5 Jan (EFE) -- A Chilean indigenous group 
on 5 January requested that the International Red Cross visit 
the southern Mexican state of Chiapas to prevent the violation 
of the human rights of the Mayan peoples of that region. 
  In a public declaration, the Mapuche Meli Wixan Mapu 
Coordinating Board states that the campesino revolt in southern 
Mexico is due to "centuries of political, economic, and cultural 
oppression," and it indicates that "this uprising is the answer 
to a slow process of ethnical-cultural death." 
  The declaration adds that Mexico's becoming a member of 
NAFTA 
"has condemned the Mayan peoples to death" because their 
production techniques "do not allow them to be competitive" with 
U.S. and Canadian markets, and this is causing "the extinction 
of those peoples." 
  The Mapuche group then makes a call to the International Red 
Cross, the Inter-American Human Rights Commission, and the UN's 
human rights organization to visit the Chiapas combat zone "in 
order to guarantee the integrity" of the indigenous peoples 
involved. 
  Coordinating board leaders Dagoberto Cachana and Alihuen 
Antileo announced that on 6 January the document will be handed 
to the Mexican Embassy in Santiago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

