<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banks Want Court Decision Clarified To Collect Tax </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0701010894 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 28 Dec 
93 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PY0701010894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Marcio Aith] </F>
  [Excerpt] The Brazilian Federation of Banks (Febraban) 
reported on 27 December 1993 that it is having problems in 
restarting the collection of the provisional tax on financial 
operations as of January 1994 because the Federal Supreme Court 
(STF) has not published the court decree (in its entirety) of 15 
December 1993 declaring the tax constitutional. 
  In that decision, the Federal Supreme Court established 
several restrictions on collections for entities considered 
immune by the Constitution and for states and municipalities. 
The court decree has not been published yet. 
  The banks allege that the Constitution restricts immunity on 
operations related to the essential activities of those 
entities, and that without the publication of the court 
decision, the banks will not be able to define what operation by 
the same entity is immune. Helio Ramos Dominguez, legal adviser 
for Febraban, said: "It is not up to the banks to define whether 
an operation is related or not to an entity's essential 
activity." 
  On 27 December 1993, the banks sent requests for 
clarification to the Federal Revenue Office and the Central 
Bank. Febraban believes it will be very difficult for the 
Federal Supreme Court to publish its decision before January -- 
the court is in recess and will return to work in February -- 
therefore, it hopes to begin collecting based on the 
clarifications from the two organizations. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

