<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports Through 6 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0601205994 </F>
<F P=103> PY0601205994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Brazil monitored through 6 
January. 
  The Mineral Resources Prospecting Company has discovered 
small deposits of platinum in Para, Rondonia, and Minas Gerais 
States for the first time since the company began prospecting in 
1991. This increases the possibility of Brazil becoming a 
platinum-producing nation. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in 
Portuguese 29 Dec 93 p 13) 
  The National Confederation of Industries reported that 
Brazilian industry will register between a 8.5-9 percent 
"exceptional" increase late in 1993. This performance will 
contribute to increasing the GDP 4.5 percent compared with 1992. 
(Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 30 Dec 93 p 9) 
  Labor Minister Walter Barelli on 30 December reported that 
as 
of 31 December the minimum salary will be 32,882 real cruzeiros, 
nearly $100, with a readjustment 75.28-percent higher than the 
December salary. (Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
31 Dec 93 Economy Section p 1) 
  The Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics, IBGE, 
on 
29 December said the unemployment rate in six Brazilian 
metropolitan regions -- Rio de Janeiro, Sao Paulo, Belo 
Horizonte, Salvador, Recife, and Porto Alegre -- was 4.57 
percent in November. This percentage was lower than October's 
4.89 percent and November 1992's 5.82 percent. The IBGE also 
said the number of employed people in the six regions grew from 
15,428,279 to 15,474,639 in October. (Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL 
in Portuguese 30 Dec 93 p 8) 

</TEXT>

