<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports Through 6 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0601211894 </F>
<F P=103> PY0601211894 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Peru monitored through 6 
January. 
  The Inter-American Development Bank on 22 December 1993 
agreed to a $100 million loan for projects to be implemented by 
the National Compensation and Social Development Fund. (Lima EL 
PERUANO in Spanish 23 Dec 93 p B1) 
  The Agriculture Ministry reported that agriculture and 
livestock production increased 9.6 percent in November compared 
with the same month last year. The accumulated production in the 
year's first 11 months was 5.4-percent higher than the same 
period last year. Agriculture production was 9.4-percent higher 
between January and November and livestock 2.2 percent. (Lima EL 
PERUANO in Spanish 23 Dec 93 p B3) 
  Foreign investment in 1993 was $1.557 billion, an increase 
of 
$265.01 million compared with 1990. The National Commission for 
Foreign Investments and Technology reported that the biggest 
increases were in mining with 35.28 percent, followed by 
industries with 32.73 percent, commerce with 13.21 percent, and 
finance with 11.10 percent. Foreign investment in the stock 
exchange went from $360 million in 1992 to $1.17 billion in 
1993. (Lima EL PERUANO in Spanish 24 Dec 93 p A2) 
  On 28 December, the congressional Energy Committee approved 
a 
draft bill on privatizating the Peruvian Telephone Company, CPT, 
and the National Telecommunications Enterprise of Peru, 
Entelperu. The state decided to sell 20 percent of its shares in 
CPT and 15 percent of Entelperu. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 29 Dec 
93 p A4) 

</TEXT>

