<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports Through 6 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0601223994 </F>
<F P=103> PY0601223994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 6 
January. 
  The Central Bank reported that the balance of payments in 
the 
year's first nine months registered a $166.7 million profit, 
including a $313.3 million deficit in the current account and a 
$480 million surplus in the capital account. The Central Bank's 
net international reserves rose $197.4 million from January to 
September 1993. (Montevideo LA MANANA in Spanish 23 Dec 93 p 47) 
  On 22 December 1993, the Central Bank reported that the GDP 
increased 1.2 percent from January to September 1993 compared 
with the same period in 1992. Agriculture and livestock 
increased 1.2 percent; construction, 16.3 percent; trade, 
restaurants, and hotels, 8.0 percent; transportation and 
communications, 9.0 percent; and others, 3.7 percent. Fishing 
dropped 2.8 percent; manufacturing industries, 8.6 percent; and 
electricity and water, 6.6 percent. (Montevideo LA MANANA in 
Spanish 23 Dec 93 p 47) 
  On 27 December 1993, the Central Bank reported that the 
Uruguayan trade balance registered a $72.3 million deficit in 
November 1993 with exports at $134.7 million and imports at $207 
million. The deficit totaled $686.9 million in the past 12 
months, with exports at $1.593 billion and imports at $2.2798 
billion. (Montevideo LA MANANA in Spanish 28 Dec 93 p 52) 
  The National Statistics Institute reported that the 
unemployment rate in Montevideo was 7.87 percent between 
September and November 1993. This rate is four percentage points 
higher than the previous quarter. (Montevideo LA MANANA in 
Spanish 31 Dec 93 p 47) 
  The Central Bank reported that the December devaluation rate 
was 2.0323 percent and the accrued devaluation rate for 1993 was 
26.88 percent. (Montevideo LA MANANA in Spanish 3 Jan 94 p 28) 
  The Central Bank on 3 January reported that the public 
sector's net foreign debt was $1.8614 billion through 31 October 
1993, a drop of 6 percent in the year's first 10 months compared 
with 1992. The public sector's gross foreign debt was $4.2046 
billion in the year's first 10 months, an increase of 1.7 
percent. Gross international reserves were $2.1787 billion 
through October 1993. The gross foreign debt in September was 
$4.2047 billion, a drop of $100,000. (Montevideo LA MANANA in 
Spanish 4 Jan 94 p 48) 
  The consumer price index was 3.67 percent in December 
compared with the same month in 1992 when it was 3.28 percent. 
The accumulated inflation rate was 52.86 percent in 1993; in 
1992 it was 58.91 percent. (Montevideo LA MANANA in Spanish 4 
Jan 94 p 4) 
  Inter-American Development Bank President Enrique Iglesias 
and President Luis Alberto Lacalle on 27 December 1993 signed a 
$38 million loan agreement to implement health projects in the 
Rincon de la Bolsa area, San Jose Department. Later they signed 
a $28 million loan agreement to improve the Labor University of 
Uruguay's technical education. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR 
ECONOMICO in Spanish 28 December 93 p 4) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

