<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRD Candidate Cardenas Comments on Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701032594 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0112 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0701032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Jose Luis Sarmenta from the "Vector 21" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The conflict in Chiapas State in no way creates 
conditions to impede the elections process which will lead to 21 
August elections, according to Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, presidential 
candidate for the Party of the Democratic Revolution [PRD], who 
has called for a suspension of hostilities in the southeastern 
state. Cardenas made his statement when visiting Ruben Lenero 
and Magdalena de las Salinas Hospitals during the celebration on 
Nurses Day. Cardenas also said that instead of being concerned 
about electoral strategies, we must seek a political solution to 
the conflict in Chiapas and prevent any further loss of human 
life. 
  [Begin Cardenas recording] Regardless of what your electoral 
preferences may be, regardless of your sympathies for the sides 
in the conflict, you are not the one directly involved in what 
is going on. We have to call on both sides to create the 
opportunity to suspend the hostilities. We need to seek 
political negotiations, because this is a political conflict, 
which emerges from the application of failed policies. We hope 
a solution may be found. [end recording] 
  Cuauhtemoc Cardenas said whether or not the uprising in 
Chiapas is promoted by Indians, the lives of Mexican people are 
being lost, and this must be stopped. The PRD presidential 
candidate said the three Chiapas bishops have the best chance of 
being heard by those involved in the conflict. He said he hopes 
the participation of the bishops could stop the bloodshed. The 
PRD presidential candidate also said he will not change his 
campaign program, adding that within the next three months he 
will be going to Chiapas State. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

