<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister on Mexican Crisis, Deployment Along Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0601225494 Guatemala City Teleonce Television in Spanish 
0400 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0601225494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City Teleonce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Telepress" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Defense Minister General Mario Enriquez has said he 
thinks the Guatemalan peace dialogue will not be altered by the 
situation in Mexico's state of Chiapas. 
  [Begin recording] [Enriquez] If reports originating in 
Mexico 
and others produced here in Guatemala confirm the participation 
of the URNG [Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity], there 
will undoubtedly be some repercussions in the peace talks. 
  [Reporter] Do you know whether those who were arrested have 
links to the URNG [words indistinct]? 
  [Enriquez] We do not have any specific information yet. We 
know there were arrests; as you know, newspapers on the morning 
of 5 January reported that. We do not have any official 
reports. As soon as we have official information, including 
names, we will let you know. As of now, all I know is what I 
read in the newspapers. Perhaps on the afternoon of 6 January we 
will have more concrete and official reports. At that time it 
is possible that the Foreign Ministry will release information 
to you; if not, I will do so as soon as information is available 
to me. At this time, the information we have we learned from 
the newspapers. 
  [Reporter] News dispatches from Mexico say the Guatemalan 
Army has reinforced the border. Is this true? 
  [Enriquez] We have not bolstered security along the border. 
On the morning of 5 January I told you that the Guatemalan 
Army's largest military presence had already been the one along 
the Mexican border. We have not increased it. If security 
there is reinforced, it is because three subversive groups are 
still present there -- the ORPA [Revolutionary Organization of 
the People in Arms], the EGP [Poor People's Guerrilla Army], and 
the FAR [Rebel Armed Forces]. This is the border where we have 
stationed the most units. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

