<F P=101> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   URNG, Government Agree on Agenda for Preliminary Meetings </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701004594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2344 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0701004594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 6 Jan (NOTIMEX) -- During a morning 
meeting today, which ended in a climate of confidence, the 
Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity (URNG) and the 
Guatemalan Government delegates agreed on an agenda for 
preliminary meetings, according to sources from both sides. 
  "There is a climate of trust," one guerrilla source 
indicated. He added that at the meeting held this morning, 
Thursday, the two sides agreed on the agenda for the talks to 
reach a peace agreement in Guatemala. The source, however, 
refrained from revealing the points in the agenda. 
  "We are advancing much more than we expected. The meeting 
has been very productive. The climate in cordial," a government 
source commented in regard to the preliminary meetings that are 
to last four days and which were called by the United Nations. 
The meetings, which are being held in a leading hotel in Mexico 
City, are attended by eight government members (three military 
officers, three civilians, and two advisers), three URNG Command 
representatives, two URNG Political-Diplomatic Commission 
delegates, and the UN-designated mediator Jean Arnault. 
  The preliminary meetings, which were called at the request 
of 
the rebels and President Ramiro de Leon Carpio's government, are 
part of an effort to continue talks that were interrupted in 
1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

