<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Says Chiapas Conflict Affecting Trade With Mexico </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0901215994 Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 7 Jan 
94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PA0901215994 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Guatemalan Foreign Trade Ministry said 
yesterday that the armed conflict at border towns in Chiapas 
State, Mexico is affecting free trade between the two countries 
and added that any delays have a direct bearing on the economy 
because exports lose their competitive edge. The ministry also 
expressed hopes that the conflict would prove temporary because 
commercial relations could be negatively affected in both Mexico 
and Guatemala. 
  The Foreign Trade Ministry emphatically denied that the 
meeting between Mexican and Guatemalan trade authorities 
scheduled for 30 November in Tabasco was suspended due to the 
recent armed conflicts, saying that the meeting was postponed 
for administrative and strategic reasons and noting that the 
conflicts had not even begun when the decision was made. The 
Foreign Trade Ministry also emphasized that talks are being held 
with Mexican economic authorities to establish new routes for 
the products. 
  If the armed conflict continues, it is highly probable that 
trade will practically come to a standstill, thus bringing 
negative consequences, the ministry concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

