<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   March Marks 1964 Incidents; U.S. Soldier Burned in Effigy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0901232194 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 2107 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0901232194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Panama City, 9 Jan (ACAN-EFE) -- Various 
political, labor, and student organizations marched today in 
Panama City to commemorate the 30th anniversary of clashes with 
U.S. troops on 9 January 1964, when 23 Panamanians died and 
diplomatic relations were temporarily broken. [passage omitted] 
  A mass was held today at the San Juan Bosco Basilica to 
honor 
the "9 January Martyrs," and dozens of people later marched 
toward the U.S. Southern Command Headquarters on Ancon Hill 
beside the canal, where they burned an effigy dressed in a U.S. 
military uniform. 
  Approximately 200 persons marched along Central Avenue 
chanting anti-U.S. and antigovernment slogans while the 
Panamanian flag flew at half mast in the distance on Ancon Hill. 
[passage omitted] 
  The absence of representatives from Guillermo Endara's 
administration was quite evident in today's events. 

</TEXT>

