<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lima Mayor on National Dialogue, Municipal Autonomy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701125194 Lima Global de Television Network in Spanish 
0100 GMT 4 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0701125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Lima Global de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Global TV News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Commenting on President Alberto Fujimori's calls for 
national dialogue, Lima Mayor Ricardo Belmont has said that all 
talks intended to revive the country's economy would be 
positive. He also said that he will submit to Congress a bill on 
the basic municipalities law in order to give them more autonomy. 
  [Begin Belmont recording] Mayors have the right to submit 
proposals. We are proposing a much more modern and more 
expeditious basic law to grant local governments what they have 
been wanting for years: an opportunity to depoliticize their 
actions and assume more executive powers, implementing public 
works programs with their properties and income to benefit 
neighborhoods. 
  I think that, as the government stated, anything that favors 
national consensus, such as the government proposal, is an 
excellent idea, because Peru needs to focus on those things that 
unite it, not on the few things that divide it. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

