<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina News Conference Prior To African Trip </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0701164994 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1000 
GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0701164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shortly before leaving on a tour that will take him 
to several African countries, Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina 
stated that the Cuban delegation will explain the reality of 
today's Cuba. 
  The foreign minister held a news conference, during which he 
broached diverse international relations subjects, emphasizing 
his tour of Ghana, Angola, Zimbabwe, Zambia, and Namibia. 
Robaina said he is going to update the foreign ministers of 
those countries on how things are in Cuba, but will also meet 
with the ministers of health, tourism, education, and others. He 
will be received by the presidents of the nations visited. 
  Regarding the internal situation in Angola, Robaina said 
that 
Cuba and Angola maintain excellent relations, which are 
experiencing a period of mutual understanding. With regard to 
relations with Chile, the foreign minister said they will be 
reestablished at the moment the Chileans consider most opportune. 
  On Cuba's relations with the United States, Robaina stated 
that while the United States' language may be less aggressive; 
the blockade has intensified. 
  [Havana Radio Progreso in Spanish at 1200 GMT on 7 January, 
in a similar report, adds: "Robaina announced: `We are obliged 
to go through Switzerland, so we have to take advantage of 
that'. There too, meetings at the Foreign Ministry are planned... 
  "The Cuban foreign minister mentioned the existence of new 
prospects for the political and economic ties between our 
country and Europe. As to the conflict in the state of Chiapas, 
he said he hoped the Mexicans would be able to find the best 
solution. Lastly, Robaina said that Cuba's situation is very 
difficult, but that we are not in a dead-end alley. Although 
1994 will not be greatly different from 1993, the spiral will 
begin moving upwards."] 

</TEXT>

