<F P=100> Antigua and Barbuda </F>
<F P=101> Barbados </F>
<H3> <TI>   Third-Quarter Unemployment 2.2 Percent Above Last Year </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0701204394 Bridgetown CANA in English 1700 GMT 7 Jan 93 </F>
<F P=103> FL0701204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bridgetown CANA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bridgetown, Barbados, 7 Jan, CANA -- Barbados 
unemployment rate during the third quarter of 1993 was pegged at 
25.5 percent, approximately 2.2 percentage points above the rate 
for the corresponding period in 1992, according to the Ministry 
of Economic Affairs. 
  "The adult population was estimated at 190,200 persons, of 
whom 126,000 comprised the labour force," the ministry reported 
in a statement. "The labour force for the period July to 
September, 1992 was 123,700 persons. The number of persons 
employed during the review period was estimated at 94,100 
persons, some 1,000 persons fewer than in the corresponding 
period in 1992." 
  Of the total labour force, approximately 31,900 persons were 
unemployed during the third quarter of 1993, compared with 
28,600 persons during the corresponding period in 1992. 
  Males unemployed increased from 20.0 percent during July to 
September 1992 to 22.4 percent during the review period. 
Unemployment among females rose by 1.9 percentage points to 
reach 28.4 percent, compared with 26.5 percent in the July to 
September quarter of 1992. The under-forty age group accounted 
for 24,700 or 77.4 per cent of the unemployed. 
  The government services employed 19,100 persons; general 
services approximately 18,100 persons; the wholesale and retail 
trade 15,000; tourism 10,100; manufacturing 8,000; construction 
and quarrying 5,000; financial, insurance and business services 
6,000; and agriculture and fisheries 4,600, while another 6,500 
found employment in other areas of activity. 
  "The rate of participation during the review period was 66.3 
percent compared with 65.6 percent for the corresponding period 
in 1992," the ministry reported. "The rate for females rose by 
1.4 percentage points to reach 59.8 percent during the review 
period while that for males remained vitually unchanged at 73.8 
percent. 
  "The number of persons not in the labour force was 64,100 
persons, some 900 fewer than during the same period in 1992. 
Approximately 25,900 were retired, 15,300 kept house, some 
12,100 were at school while 8,500 were either incapacitated or 
voluntarily idle." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

