<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Survey Reveals Public Opposition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701132194 Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in 
Spanish 1200 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0701132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "Caracol's 0600 to 0900" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Government explanations notwithstanding, Colombians 
feel the presence of U.S. soldiers in Colombia is not good. 
This was seen in answers to Caracol's "Topic of the Day" 
question: 33.8 percent of those surveyed said it violates 
national sovereignty; 23.4 percent said Colombia has people to 
build a school or a health center, which are the projects the 
soldiers will work on; 18 percent felt the U.S. military 
presence is an indication that these soldiers might invade the 
country; 14.3 percent felt the goal is to install radar 
stations; and 10.4 percent stated the government must fully 
explain the U.S. military presence in the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

