<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Real Mission' Questioned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0801023394 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0801023394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Miriam Ortiz from the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The presence of U.S. soldiers in Colombia is 
relatively new. Although it is known that they are posted 
throughout the country, their real mission here is not clear. 
It has been said that they are here to carry out civic work, 
but other sources insist they are participating in 
counternarcotics operations. 
  Several contingents of U.S. soldiers have arrived in 
Colombia 
to participate in the so-called cooperation plan in the struggle 
against drug trafficking. Several soldiers traveled to Leticia 
in the Amazon Region to install radar to control clandestine 
flights in the southern part of the country. That decision 
generated an extensive debate in Congress. Leticia residents 
protested, saying that heavily armed soldiers had occupied the 
streets. 
  A group of U.S. soldiers also arrived on San Andres Island 
to 
install a radar to control aircraft coming from the United 
States. Approximately 50 persons from the U.S. Navy, known as 
SeaBees, arrived to build a base equipped with several patrol 
boats on the banks of the Guaviare River. A similar mission is 
being conducted in the Puerto Lopez area, Meta Department. 
Soldiers from Ft. Rucker, Alabama, are stationed at Malaga Bay. 
  According to authorities from both countries, the troops 
arrived in Valle del Cauca to build a school and a clinic and to 
repair several roads in Juanchaco. The arrival of troops and 
their equipment in helicopters and warships has made residents 
of those areas skeptical; some believe they came with a 
different objective. 
  A total of six U.S. bases have been built throughout the 
country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50855 </DOCNO>
