<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Diego H. Canal from the "NTC News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Among the gringo workers who arrived at Juanchaco, 
there are professors whose speciality is not included in the 
education program of the small school they are building. The 
U.S. troops did not come to Colombia only to build civilian 
facilities; they have also gone into areas of conflict to 
conduct military training. 
  [Begin General Octavio Gnecco, Naval Infantry commander, 
recording] They have sent several U.S. Marines as temporary 
instructors, especially in river combat techniques. [end 
recording] 
  Several training exercises have already been held at a base 
called Barranco, located in Guaviare. The foreign military 
personnel, together with several engineers, have arrived with 
their weapons in the area. Just as in the Malaga Bay and Puerto 
Lopez areas, the military have been sent by the United States to 
help the Colombian Navy build several facilities. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Have those 
instructors also given antiguerrilla courses in Colombia? 
  [Gnecco] Yes, on several occasions. Based on a U.S. Army 
offer, we held a one-month training course for our troops in San 
Jose del Guaviare. [end recording] 
  This type of military training has also been given in Puerto 
Legizamo and, according to the Colombian Navy, is also part of 
the cooperation agreement with the United States. What we do 
not know is, as is happening in other parts of Colombia, 
military advisers are also arriving, and not as professors of 
the school they are going to build in the Malaga Bay area. 

</TEXT>

