<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Details on Downed Venezuelan National Guard Helicopter </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0801200694 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0801200694 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from the "NTC News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Reports on the crash of a Venezuelan National Guard 
helicopter in Colombian territory continue to become more 
confusing. We have arrived in the zone and have established 
various issues there: First, the Venezuelan helicopter had 
landed in Colombian territory hours before the crash; second, it 
was not attacked by Colombian guerrilla groups, but it suffered 
an accident because it was carrying too much weight--and its 
crew members arbitrarily arrested various Colombian fishermen. 
Third, the shots fired from the aircraft were actually fired by 
the Venezuelan military to justify their actions. 
  The Army Commander has this document on his desk, the 
official report sent by the Colombian Armed Forces concerning 
the incident. The document's contents reveal: The confidential 
report sent in recently by the 2d Operation Command to the 
General Command in Santa Fe de Bogota registers, step by step, 
the operation executed yesterday by the Venezuelan military. 
Colonel Arcesio Barrero narrates to Army Commander General 
Hernan Jose Guzman the actions executed by the Venezuelan 
National Guard members. For example, he says the military 
suddenly entered Colombian territory, beat up civilians, 
insulted them, stole their money, and threatened them with 
death. The document becomes the strongest evidence of a 
violation of sovereignty that the government has in its power. 
It is the report from an appalled high-ranking Colombian Army 
officer who tells his superior about the Venezuelan Army's 
capacity for aggression. 
  The document clearly establishes there was never an 
intervention by the Colombian guerrilla forces, and the bullet 
holes in the helicopter were caused by the Venezuelan military 
members' own weapons to claim the aircraft had fallen due to a 
subversive action. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50861 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat006_o_94010" </HT>


