<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Attorney General: Tax Still Valid </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701181994 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 6 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0701181994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Excerpt] The attorney general of the Republic and the 
finance minister have commented on the ruling issued by the 3d 
Court for Tax Issues and agreed it does not invalidate the 
collection of the value-added tax [IVA]. Instead, it urges the 
Executive Branch to better publicize the law. 
  [Begin recording] [Attorney General Ricardo Ernst Contreras] 
The law is still in effect. A court ruling in connection with a 
request submitted by anyone does not derogate a law. Laws are 
only derogated by other laws. Laws are also derogated when 
someone submits an appeal for annulment because the law violates 
the constitution -- and the appeal has sufficient grounds. This 
can involve the whole law or some of its provisions. 
  Also, a law can be rescinded in connection with a given 
process because one of the interested parties claims the law 
violates the Constitution. However, the ruling issued by such a 
court in connection with such an appeal obviously cannot 
derogate a law. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50868 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat006_t_94003" </HT>


