<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Asks Merchants To Apply IVA </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0801033994 Caracas Venezolana de Television Network in 
Spanish 2350 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0801033994 </F>
<F P=104>  Caracas Venezolana de Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Finance Ministry has urged merchants to charge 
the value-added tax [IVA] and asked consumers not to refuse to 
pay it, noting that noncompliance with this mandate will be 
punished according to the law. 
  Finance Ministry Legal Adviser Rafael Silva said only the 
Supreme Court of Justice can abolish the IVA law, and therefore 
it cannot be suspended by a judge, because this would be 
unconstitutional. He added that the legal basis for the writ of 
amparo is not clear, because it does not specify what right was 
violated and places the state in a defenseless legal position 
[indefension judicial]. Furthermore, the writ of amparo demands 
from the government additional information on the implementation 
of the IVA -- a measure that is not required when a law is 
implemented. He stressed that this tax cannot be suspended. 
  [Begin Silva recording] The Finance Ministry has no legal 
authority and no legal instrument enabling it to suspend the 
implementation of a law. We cannot do that. In any event, what 
the Finance Ministry could probably do after being legally 
notified of the decision is to instruct customs not to charge 
the IVA, or not collect the IVA, which is the only tributary 
obligation this would entail for the Finance Ministry. [end 
recording] 
  The Finance Ministry has not taken any action against the 
judge who issued a ruling eliminating the IVA. Nevertheless, 
Finance Minister Adviser Alcides Villalba has requested his 
dismissal. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-50870 </DOCNO>
