<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   PROCESO Director Declines To Mediate; Menchu Accepts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0901214794 Paris AFP in Spanish 1929 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0901214794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 9 Jan (AFP) -- Mexican journalist 
Julio Scherer, director of the PROCESO weekly, today declined an 
invitation from the Zapatista National Liberation Army (EZLN) to 
mediate an eventual dialogue with the government. 
  In today's edition of PROCESO, Scherer said: "I appreciate 
the inclusion of my name with those of Bishop Samuel Ruiz and 
Ms. Rigoberta Menchu," the other two persons proposed by the 
EZLN. 
  "However, as a journalist I am committed to impartiality, 
which would be difficult for me to maintain in a double role as 
mediator and reporter of the events we are experiencing," said 
Scherer. 
  "Thus I must exclusively fulfill the rules of my 
profession," 
he concluded. 
  Today Samuel Ruiz, bishop of San Cristobal de Las Casas, 
announced in his homily that he accepted the offer to try to 
mediate the dialogue proposed by the EZLN, whereas the answer is 
yet to come from Menchu, a Guatemalan Indian who received the 
Nobel Peace Price in 1992. 
  In the same edition, PROCESO disclosed that the EZLN had 
asked the three to "respond publicly to our proposal and, if the 
response is positive, mediate in this dialogue between the 
struggling poor people and their hangmen. For that purpose you 
are invited to the EZLN General Command in Lacandona jungle, 
where you will always be well received and protected so you can 
receive our proposals in writing." 
  [Hamburg DPA in Spanish at 2032 GMT on 9 January 94 adds 
that 
Rigoberta Menchu has "confirmed today her willingness to accept 
the role of mediator in the conflict, although she expressed the 
need to first know the responses from Ruiz and Scherer and to 
have guaranteed approval from Mexican President Carlos Salinas 
de Gortari."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

