<F P=101> Chiapas Crisis </F>
<H3> <TI>   Michoacan Governor Denies Existence of Armed Groups </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0901174494 Mexico City Radio Mil Network in Spanish 1400 
GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0901174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio Mil Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Maria de los Angeles Garcia; from "The City" </F>
newscast] 
  [Text] State Governor Ausencio Chavez Hernandez has denied 
the existence of armed groups in Michoacan. He has described 
the attempts two days ago by unidentified individuals to down a 
Federal Electricity Commission high-tension electricity pylon, 
located 10 km from Periban, as an isolated incident. 
  Chavez has met with reporters at the State Government House 
and said there is a climate of work, calm, and social peace in 
the state. The governor also denied that dynamite or 
blowtorches were used in the attempt to down the high-tension 
pylon, and he revealed that a fretsaw had been used to cut the 
base of the tower. Chavez added that the sabotage had been 
perpetuated by people who wanted to stand out by following 
examples set in other areas, referring to the events in Chiapas. 
Chavez reported that the high-tension pylon had not been 
damaged and that the electricity supply had not been cut off. 

</TEXT>

