<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Human Rights Group Asks Mexico To Avoid Ethnic Cleansing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0701124494 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 6 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0701124494 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Quito -- The Latin American Human Rights Association 
[ALDHU] has called on the Mexican Government not to implement 
scorched earth or ethnic cleansing policies to deal with the 
current violent situation in Chiapas State, Mexico. The Mexican 
state, one of the most powerful in Latin America, has enough 
operational and military instruments to resolve this situation 
without having to resort to scorched earth or ethnic cleansing 
policies, according to Chilean Juan de Dios Parra, executive 
secretary of the ALDHU. 
  The expression scorched earth refers to the use of intense 
military bombings to eliminate all traces of human, animal, and 
plant life in a specific area. Ethnic cleansing refers to the 
elimination of a certain race. 
  Parra also added that the peasant rebellion of the past six 
days in Mexico is doomed to failure and that more than 500 
people have been killed, most of them innocent civilians. 
According to ALDHU spokesman Cesar Mosquera, the figure of 500 
dead was obtained by the organization after telephone 
conversations with Mexican human rights organizations. Official 
figures from Mexico have only reported the killing of 102 people 
even though Catholic Church sources in Mexico estimate the 
number of people killed could reach 400. 
  Clashes between the Mexican Army and peasants from the 
so-called Zapatista National Liberation Army have been going on 
since 1 January. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

