<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Menem Blames Mexican Chiapas Uprising on `Mercenaries' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1101001094 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
2036 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1101001094 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 10 Jan (NA) -- President Carlos Menem 
today blamed the appearance of the self-styled Zapatista 
National Liberation Army (EZLN) in the southern Mexican state of 
Chiapas on "the presence of many mercenaries and professional 
subversives." 
  He also denied the charges pressed by six Mexican human 
rights organizations of the alleged genocide of civilians, 
wondering "what could be done if when subversion takes to arms, 
those who are killing people are said to be preserving human 
rights." 
  "Our interpretation is the same we had for the subversion in 
Argentina, even though the situation is not similar and has 
deeper connotations, such as the ethnical side. In Argentina, 
subversion tried to reach power after the declaration of 
liberated zones such as that in Tucuman," the president said. 
  In a conversation with journalists accredited to Government 
House, Menem said the situation in Mexico was not "improvised, 
because even if at the beginning it appeared to be something 
unplanned, it was later seen that the EZLN was well organized." 
  The president admitted that "displeasure" is the main reason 
for the creation of subversive organizations that "take 
advantage of this to engage in something broader, which does not 
meet the people's demands and which upsets legal order." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

